  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - The diagnostic approach to hemoptysis should be guided by the clinical presentation, severity of bleeding, and available resources. High-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) of the chest has become the imaging modality of choice for the initial evaluation of hemoptysis, with sensitivity superior to chest radiography for detecting bronchiectasis, small parenchymal lesions, and vascular abnormalities. HRCT can identify the bleeding site in up to 80% of cases and the specific cause in 60-77%, making it an essential tool in evaluating patients with hemoptysis, even those with a normal chest radiograph. HRCT is particularly useful for detecting bronchiectasis, which may not be apparent on chest radiography. Bronchoscopy remains an important diagnostic tool, especially for localizing the bleeding site and evaluating endobronchial lesions, but its yield is maximized when performed after HRCT has identified areas of concern. For patients with massive hemoptysis or those in whom bronchoscopy and HRCT fail to identify a cause, bronchial arteriography may be performed both for diagnosis and potential therapeutic embolization. Additional tests such as complete blood count, coagulation studies, urinalysis, and autoimmune markers may be necessary depending on the clinical suspicion.",
