  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Aspergilloma (fungus ball) is a conglomeration of fungal hyphae, inflammatory cells, fibrin, mucus, and tissue debris that typically develops in a preexisting pulmonary cavity. Such cavities are commonly due to prior tuberculosis, sarcoidosis, bronchiectasis, or other bullous lung diseases. Aspergillus fumigatus is the most frequent causative species. Clinical manifestations range from asymptomatic to severe hemoptysis, which is the most common symptom and can be life-threatening due to erosion of bronchial arteries. Other symptoms may include cough, dyspnea, and malaise. The diagnosis is suggested by radiographic findings: a mobile intracavitary mass with an air crescent visible on chest radiography or CT. The \"air crescent sign\" represents air between the fungal ball and the cavity wall. Serum precipitins (IgG antibodies) against Aspergillus are positive in >90% of cases, while galactomannan antigen is typically negative. Treatment is often challenging, with antifungal therapy showing limited efficacy due to poor drug penetration into the cavity. Bronchial artery embolization may be used to control hemoptysis, but definitive management for recurrent or severe hemoptysis is surgical resection when feasible.",
