  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Inhalation of toxic gases or fumes can cause acute respiratory distress due to direct chemical injury to the tracheobronchial tree and lungs. Chlorine gas is a highly water-soluble irritant that primarily affects the upper respiratory tract and can cause immediate symptoms including cough, choking, eye and throat irritation, and chest tightness. With higher concentrations or prolonged exposure, it can penetrate deeper into the respiratory tract, causing bronchospasm, pulmonary edema, and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). Clinical manifestations include dyspnea, wheezing, hemoptysis, and hypoxemia. Chest radiographs may show patchy infiltrates, and pulmonary function tests typically reveal obstructive patterns. Management of acute inhalation injury includes removal from exposure, administration of supplemental oxygen, and bronchodilators for bronchospasm. Systemic corticosteroids may help reduce airway inflammation, though their efficacy is not definitively established. Intubation and mechanical ventilation are reserved for severe cases with progressive respiratory failure. Most patients with mild to moderate exposure improve within 24-48 hours, though some may develop reactive airways dysfunction syndrome (RADS), a condition characterized by persistent asthma-like symptoms following a single high-level exposure to an irritant.",
