  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Goodpasture's syndrome is an autoimmune disease characterized by the production of pathogenic antibodies against type IV collagen in the glomerular and alveolar basement membranes, leading to a pulmonary-renal syndrome of glomerulonephritis and pulmonary hemorrhage. The disease typically affects young men, with peaks of incidence in the second and third decades, and again in the sixth and seventh decades. Clinical manifestations include hemoptysis, dyspnea, anemia, hematuria, proteinuria, and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis leading to renal failure. Serologic testing for anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) antibodies is the cornerstone of diagnosis, with positivity in 85-90% of cases. Linear deposition of IgG along the glomerular basement membrane on immunofluorescence of renal biopsy specimens is diagnostic. Precipitating factors may include respiratory tract infections, cigarette smoking, exposure to hydrocarbon solvents, and influenza. Treatment includes plasmapheresis to remove circulating antibodies, combined with immunosuppression using corticosteroids and cyclophosphamide. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent irreversible renal damage and life-threatening pulmonary hemorrhage. The prognosis is poor when treatment is initiated after serum creatinine exceeds 5-6 mg/dL or when dialysis is required.",
