  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Cystic fibrosis (CF) is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) gene, leading to abnormal ion transport across epithelial surfaces. Pulmonary manifestations include chronic bacterial infections, bronchiectasis, and progressive respiratory failure. Hemoptysis occurs in approximately 1% of patients per year and can range from blood-streaked sputum to massive bleeding. Management of acute pulmonary exacerbations includes intravenous antibiotics (typically a combination of an aminoglycoside and an antipseudomonal beta-lactam), aggressive airway clearance techniques, and bronchodilators. Dornase alfa (recombinant human DNase), which cleaves extracellular DNA in CF sputum, reduces sputum viscosity and improves pulmonary function. For mild to moderate hemoptysis (<240 mL/24 h), the treatment focuses on the underlying exacerbation with antibiotics, continued airway clearance techniques, and correction of any coagulopathy. Massive hemoptysis (>240 mL/24 h or compromised respiratory status) may require bronchial artery embolization or, rarely, surgical resection. CFTR modulators, such as ivacaftor, lumacaftor, and elexacaftor, are now available for specific CFTR mutations and have shown significant improvements in lung function, exacerbation rates, and quality of life.",
